title: No. 4 CNU women spike Salisbury in volleyball after falling behind by a set
text:
No. 4 CNU women spike Salisbury in volleyball after falling behind by a set Compiled by Daily Press 
COLLEGES: 
Women's volleyball: 
Hannah Miller had 17 kills, Mathews' Maddie McCann had 11 kills and Jamestown High graduate Briana Sutton made 19 digs as Christopher Newport, ranked fourth in Division III, rallied past Salisbury 21-25, 25-19, 25-23, 25-22 Wednesday at Freeman Center. 
Rachel Conway had 46 assists for CNU (16-2, 2-0 Capital Athletic Conference). 
Katie Stouffer had 17 kills and Nicole Venturelli 16 apiece for Salisbury (14-7, 1-1), which led 17-13 in the second set before the Captains turned around the match. ... 
Virginia’s Anna Walsh was named the Atlantic Coast Conference Freshman of the Week for the third consecutive time and the fourth occasion this season. She has helped the Cavaliers (11-4, 3-1 ACC) win six of their last seven matches. 
Men’s soccer: 
Virginia junior Patrick Foss was named the ACC Defensive Player of the Week. He scored on free kicks of 40 and 50 yards to give the Cavaliers a 3-2 win Friday over Louisville. 
The latter goal, from just beyond midfield, was named the No. 3 highlight on ESPN’s SportsCenter top 10 that night. 
Men’s golf: 
Christopher Newport’s Matt DiSalvo was named the Capital Athletic Conference Golfer of the Week for the fourth time in his career. 
He led the Captains to first place in the Bay Creek Invitational in Cape Charles and sixth place at the Royal Lakes Oglethorpe Fall Invitational in Flowery Branch, Ga. 
The reigning CAC Player of the Year, DiSalvo has posted a career-best 74.5 stroke average through three tournaments this fall. 
Softball: 
Three members of the 2015 Norfolk State squad were named to the National Fastpitch Coaches Association All-America Scholar Athlete team. 
Departed senior Alina Moriarty, current senior Whitney Williams and current sophomore Seana Moriarty were NSU’s three honorees. 
Women’s tennis: 
William and Mary’s Leeza Nemchinov went 1-1 in the qualifying bracket for the Riviera/Intercollegiate Tennis Association All-American Championships in Pacific Palisades, Calif. 
Ranked 46th nationally in singles, she beat No. 68-ranked Jean Runglerdkriangkrai of Pepperdine 6-3, 3-6, 6-4, then lost 6-4, 3-6, 6-4 to No. 29 Ellen Perez of Georgia, who earned a spot in the 32-player main draw. 
U.Va.’s Stephanie Nauta won two singles matches to advance to the final round of qualifying, and she teamed with Danielle Collins for an 8-6 victory against Stanford in doubles qualifying. 
Collins and fellow Cavalier Julia Elbaba were invited directly to the main singles draw. 
PRO BASKETBALL: 
Brandon Rozzell, a senior guard on VCU’s 2011 Final Four team, was named the Player of the Week in a Danish league. 
He had 33 points and nine rebounds in one game for the Svendborg Rabbits.
